body:
@chrisvest I think the following issue seems still exists in the newest 4.1.72.Final version.

"When thread2 is recycling objects which created by thread1, if thread1 was finished/terminated at this moment, then thread2 will still put the objects back to thread1's queue, which is not necessary."

Corrects me if I wrongly understood it.

@chrisvest  What about we store the thread to `WeakReference` in `io.netty.util.Recycler.LocalPool`, and do the `null` check while recycling, like the following:
```
private static final class LocalPool<T> {
    ...
    private final WeakReference<Thread> threadRef = new WeakReference<>(Thread.currentThread());
    ...
}

private static final class DefaultHandle<T> implements Handle<T> {
    @Override
    public void recycle(Object object) {
        ...
        if (localPool.threadRef.get() == null) {
            return; // Do not need to recycle;
        }
        ...
    }
}
```
WDYT?
